{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_immokalee_ver01/data/sn95047334/00529042474/1958040301/0189.xml":{"full_text":"About Your Home\nby Frances Dell\nTo get best results when you\nare decorating a narrow room,\nyou will find that light flooring\nand light walls are your best\nchoice. If wood paneling is used,\nit should be light pine paneling,\nnot heavier woods. Ceilings must\ntake to the light look, too. A\ngood trick to know is that a little\nblue added to the white painted\nceiling will lend height to your\nroom.\nPaintings across the long wall\nmay help create depth. A large\npainting should be chosen if you\nwant the maximum effect. A\nFloor Covering\nInlaid linoleum, rubber,\n\u25bcinyL cork all type*\nCounter Top\nWork\nAll Types including\nFormica\nExpert Installation\nBELL-SHELFER\nair\ny avm<v ^Keaiea\n77\nI\nSUBER JOHNSON CO.\n115 W\u00ab Jefferson Quincy\nwe cmosi\nV ALCOA\nXaluTmTmum\nHOORHO ANO SCWMO\nJL_\n^ALURMHOm\nI\n11\nV \\\\\\vX\\w HEi\nm \u00abI\nWhen you enclose a building with Alcoa\u00ae Aluminum, you pay the\nbill and forget it. There'* no painting. No rusting away. No rotting.\nYou cut repairs and upkeep to the bare minimum. Think what thi*\nMa save you Hi 10 year*. Twenty years! Even longer!\nIn cooperation with leading agricultural colleges, Alcoa has de\nveloped plans for dairy, poultry, storage and utility buildings that\nMa be erected at savings up to 75%. We have a complete catalog\nat these plans for you to choose from.\nAlcoa Roofing and Siding is made from a stronger, tougher alloy.\nIt comes in both standard 26\u201d width and in the new 48\u201d width that\ngoes up faster with les* waste at laps. We stock all\nsizes and patterns as well as Alcoa Nails, Flashing.\nValley and Ridge Roll.\nWhy not plan to erect aluminum buildings?\nThey cost less, stay up to 15 degree* cooler in\nsummer, provide extra fire protection, minimize\nbuilding maintenance.\nNfW ALCOA ALUMINUM OATtS\nAvailable for opening* 10\\ 12\\ 14' and 16'. XL on't sag, twist, warp\nor buckle. Stronger, lighter, more\nstockproof than anything else\navailable. See them here.\nDO AS ANY GOOD BUILDER WOULD\nS-P-E-C-I-F-Y\nALCOA\nROOFING SIDING\nFLETCHER COMPANY\nHIGHLAND 2-2215 GREENSBORO\nIN LAST PRESENTATION\u2014 Mrs. John Whitney (left),\nwife of the U. S. Ambassador to Britain, is shown\nin London with some of the 489 American debu\ntantes presented to Queen Elizabeth at Bucking\nham Palace. The Queen announced she has de\ncided to end the presentation ceremony next year\nand this may be the last. From bottom (clock\nwise) are: Mrs. Whitney; Deborah Dunning, New\nYork; Mary-Rowland Haight, Waterbury, Conn.;\nmirror is often used to achieve a\nfeeling of depth, also.\nAvoid heavy drapery materials\nin a narrow room. These will\ngive the appearance of closing in\nthe room even more.\nAvoid such deep colors as red,\ngreen, or blue when decorating\nthe very narrow room. Choose\ninstead pastels or off-white. Del\nicate patterns in wall paper or\nfabrics may be used with suc\ncess. Remember that it is al\nways a good idea not to use dra\nmatic patterns in a small room in\nthe upholstery, or drapery ma\nterials.\nSmall-scale furniture adds\nwidth to the room. Take advan\ntage of Danish and Swedish de\nsigns.\nIt is best not to put the sofa\nunder the window of a narrow\nroom, as this will give you addi\ntional wall space to fill up where\nas the window itself may serve\nto break up wall space. Picture\nwindows are wonderful to add\ndepth to a narrow room. How\never, keep in mind that a large\nwindow must look out on some\nattractive view to be of any im\nportance in a room. Picture\nwindows with no view except\none of the street or your neigh\nbor\u2019s clothes-line should have\ndrapes to break the outlook.\nLIGHT WEIGHT\nLONGER LIFE\nLESS UPKEEP\nAmanda Haight, Waterbury, Conn.; Barbara and\nCynthia Hunter, Sherman, Tex.; Margaretta\nMaganini, Greenwich, Conn.; Virginia Lee Mar\nchant, Mathews, Va.; Jacqueline Anne Mars, The\nPlains, Va.; Jaymes Harriet Van Wolkenten,\nMadison, Wis.; Imogene Shannon Young, San An\ntonio, Tex.; Susan Vick, Coopertown, N. Y., and\nJoan Nichols. New York. The Queen held her cus\ntomary tea party for the debs. (International)\nGREETING A MEMORIAV-John Gudz, head housonan at a New\nYork hotel, looks sadly at a huge poster of the late producer,\nMike Todd. It hangs above the dais where the plane crash vic\ntim was to have received the \u201cShowman of The Year\u201d award\nfrom the Friars Chib, a theatrical organization. ffatemotioftaD\nFLORIDA FRUIT VEGETABLE ASSOCIATION\u2019S Research\nCommittee was told of new research facilities for the state\u2019s\nfruit and vegetable industry by Dr. Matthew K. Veldhuis,\n[left, seated], in charge of the USDA Fruit and Vegetable\nProducts Laboratory at Winter Haven. The new $750,000\nfacility is a part of the Southern Utilization Research and\nDevelopment Division, USDA, New Orleans. Participating in\nthe discussion with Dr. Veldhuis were [seated, L to R] L. T.\nThompson, Sarasota, chairman of FFVA\u2019s Research Committee;\nGeorge Wedgworth, Belle Glade, vice chairman; and [Standing,\nL to R] Bruce Gray, Hastings; and C. B. Streetman, Vero\nBeach, committee members.\nTV-ON-TNB-WAUL\u2014This small -checkerboard\" represents an\nimportant step in the development of a screen to bring tele\nvision-on-the-wall into the average living room. Called an\n\u201celf\u201d screen, it contrasts ratios between light and dark areas.\nAlthough these squares are half-inch across, on a quarter-inch\npanel, those to be used on a TV receiver would be only a few\nthousandths of an inch wide. The screen is being developed by\nthe Westinghouse Research Laboratory at Schenectady. N. Y.\nGADSDEN COUNTY TIMES, QUINCY, FLORIDA, THURSDAY, APRIL 3, 1958\nlEFL I C T I\nTRADCMARK CORR. 19M\n...with JAMES C. INGEBRETSEN\nPresident, Spiritual Mobilization\nHere are the headlines that\nstood out in the news over the\nweekend:\n\u201cEisenhower Asks Huge Boost\nin Spending to Halt Recession\u2014\nWould Use 7 Billions for Public\nPropjects, Highways, Defense,\u201d\n\u201cFaster Action to Lift Employ\nment Urged \u2014Eight GOP Sena\ntors Issue Call,\u201d \u201cNew Boost in\nDebt Limit Looms if Slump Con\ntinues\u2014 Congress Also May Re\nmain in Session Longer.\u201d\nThe eight GOP Senators who\nissued the call for faster action\nreportedly said, \u201cAnd unless the\ngovernment acts promptly and\neffectively to end recession, it\ncannot succeed in its long-range\neffort to control inflation,\u201d ap\nparently completely disregard\ning the fact that similar \u201cpump\npriming\u201d by the New Deal was\nnot only futile but also was the\nstart of the inflation that has\ndevalued our money by more\nthan half.\nI ^fjll Your Easter Basket I\nM hoops of good food ftom I\nIIiUmL1 IiUmL I\nI Tommy Says: Come and get this fine v| UMIUIBr\nI Hr V: Fresh Meatl vMWMz\nGrade A Large Smoked Country Cured ^SSSS!^\nHENS it HAMS 49'\nI Homemade Pan\nFresh Caught Nice Size I\nI Mill I FT ausa 9 e o\u201c|\nI Qc Wieners |b 49 c I\nI POUND I White Boiling M I\nIcudiu Pit QOc BACON\u00bb> 19 I\n^^l MIVII \u25a0\u25a0J* Grade ADr Dr. Cut-up or Whole\nLarge Ones AnywayYou Want \"E\u00ae f 1\nI FREE! BABY CHICKS j\nI TO CHILDREN ACCOMPANIED\nI BY PARENTS W I\nSUGARS 39i pro\nwith other Purchases ^ML^ edium _\nI Kraft's Apple\n20 Oz. WM V Fresh Tender String\nI JELL T a,\u2122 BEANS b 29c I\nI TBI BE 020 Oz. UU^ft'Red Kiln Dried Sweet A A I-\nI I Kir E<s cans I S Potatoes 2 lbs. n>C|\nI Perfection Long Grain\nIrICE 3 29 c BANANAS\nPURE LARD 10 lb\nI g9C g l APPLES 2 ibs. 29< I\n111 CALL FOR YOUR PLANNED\nI 'MI EASTER DINNER MENU\nFOODS\u2014 I\nIWSr'S 8 19\u2018\nV IPB ANTI Colonial Frozen Brussel _\nI wW \u201cKJJ i I Sprouts 35c J\nI I Broccoli 35c\nOn Nov. 15, 1957, the following\nappeared in The Wall Street\nJournal: \u201cOne reason many of\nus can\u2019t afford a European vaca\ntion is because our dollars made\nthe trip without us.\u201d\nChange \u201cEuropean\u201d to \u201cWash\nington\u201d in that sentence and you\nhave the main reason for the\ncurrent recession.\nThe most encouraging head\nline we saw over the particular\nweekend mentioned above was\nthis one: \u201cSix Billion Tax Slash\nUrged by Rep. Simpson.\u201d If that\ncould be arranged \u2014and coupled\nwith a seven-billion-dollar cut in\nFederal spending (instead of a\nlike-sized boost in such spend\ning) \u2014the recession would be\nended overnight. But, of course,\nunder a collectivist bureaucracy,\nthat is not the way things is done.\nI\u2019m one of the innocent by\nstanders whose travel plans were\nlast week disrupted by an air\nline strike. Before the year is\nout, millions of others will be\nsimilarly caught as union lead\ners use naked power to achieve\nvictory in an industrial dispute.\nNow, the achievement of any\nhonorable goal brings a healthy\nsense of elation \u2014not only to the\nprincipals concerned but also to\nsympathetic or even merely in\nterested bystanders.\nBut, as Saint-Exupery said,\n\u201cThere are victories that are\ndefeats, and there are defeats\nthat turn out to be victories.\u201d\nThe healthy sense of elation\ndepends very largely on whether\nor not the goal attained is an\nhonorable one \u2014and, of course,\nwhether or nob it has been at\ntained honorably.\nIf not, there is that in most of\nus that causes the event to leave\na bitter taste in the soul.\nWe can see this plainly today\nin our industrial relationships.\nEvery strike leaves its bitter re\nsidue of wrongdoing. Every hon\norable goal attained through gen-\nPAGE THREE\nuine cooperation and brotherly\nkindness brings an exuberant\nsenses of elation that makes even\nthose who are only bystanders\nfeel good.\nThese are the simple facts. We\nall know them. And Jesus said,\n\u201cIf ye know these things, happy\nare ye if ye do them.\u201d Why,\nthen, do we not always do what\nwe know will bring to us, and\nothers, happiness\u2014instead of so\nfrequently doing just the oppo\nsite?\nIsn\u2019t it funny how some wo\nmen spend so much time on\nbeauty treatments.","height":"29064","width":"19860"}}
